The following Rust function computes factorial using recursion.

fn factorial(n: u64) -> u64 {
    if n == 0 {
        return 1;
    }
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
}

The base case returns one because the multiplicative identity ensures the product terminates correctly. Each recursive call pushes a new stack frame with a decremented argument. When n reaches zero, the chain unwinds by multiplying the return values in last-in-first-out order. For inputs larger than roughly twenty, the result overflows a sixty-four-bit integer, so the type limits practical usage despite the algorithmic simplicity.
